Ahh yes — the issue happened because of this:

rm default

You deleted the actual Nginx config file 😄
and then created a symbolic link pointing back to itself:

/etc/nginx/sites-available/myweb
   -> /etc/nginx/sites-available/default

But default itself no longer exists.

That’s why:

Too many levels of symbolic links

and Nginx failed to start.

Fix Properly 🚀
Step 1 — Remove Broken Symlink

Run:

sudo rm /etc/nginx/sites-available/myweb
Step 2 — Recreate Proper Nginx Config

Create new config file:

sudo nano /etc/nginx/sites-available/myweb

Paste this:

server {
    listen 80;
    server_name _;

    root /opt/dump-task/sarab;

    index index.html;

    location / {
        try_files $uri $uri/ /index.html;
    }
}

Save:

CTRL + O
Enter
CTRL + X
Step 3 — Enable Site

Now create symlink correctly:

sudo ln -s /etc/nginx/sites-available/myweb /etc/nginx/sites-enabled/
Step 4 — Remove Old Broken Symlink (if exists)

Check:

ls /etc/nginx/sites-enabled/

If you see default, remove it:

sudo rm /etc/nginx/sites-enabled/default
Step 5 — Test Nginx Config

VERY IMPORTANT:

sudo nginx -t

If successful, you’ll see:

syntax is ok
test is successful
Step 6 — Start Nginx
sudo systemctl start nginx

Then:

sudo systemctl enable nginx

Then verify:

sudo systemctl status nginx

You should see:

active (running)
Step 7 — Fix Permissions
sudo chmod -R 755 /opt/dump-task/sarab
sudo chown -R www-data:www-data /opt/dump-task/sarab
Step 8 — Open Browser

Visit:

http://YOUR_PUBLIC_IP

Now your frontend page should load 🎉
